{"type":"message","id":"d8809bbd","parentId":"335620e3","timestamp":"2026-03-24T14:56:17.741Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_0wjg84lkk6tg_2","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# Pulse: 2026-03-24 105456\n\n## Applied Mutations\nNo mutations applied this cycle.\nRejected: experiment (missing)\n\n## LLM Response\n<think>\r\nLet me review the current state and the pending actions. The most actionable item seems to be the CFI-weighted compression experiment that was flagged as \"Next\" in the Phase 1 Advancement notes.\r\n\r\nLooking at what's available:\r\n1. CFI_RESULTS.md has been created with findings about CFI analysis\r\n2. The next step is to implement a CFI-weighted compression experiment\r\n\r\nI should create an experiment design or implement a script that compares CFI-weighted compression vs frequency baseline for next-pulse prediction.\r\n\r\nLet me look at what files exist and what would be the most concrete next action. I need to advance toward the pending items:\r\n- CFI-weighted compression experiment\r\n- CFI filtering to remove metaprogramming contamination\r\n- Distinguish constant format from research trajectory\r\n\r\nA concrete action would be to design/run the CFI-weighted compression experiment. Let me create a document outlining the experiment or implement it.\r\n\r\nActually, I should create a concrete experiment script or design document that can actually run the comparison. Let me draft something specific.\r\n\r\nLooking at the CFI_RESULTS.md findings:\r\n- 44.8% have CFI=0 (pure noise/metaprogramming artifacts)\r\n- 5.7% have CFI>=0.7 (true causal anchors)\r\n- Mean CFI is 0.181\r\n\r\nThe experiment would be:\r\n1. Take a set of pulse documents\r\n2. Compare frequency-based compression (baseline) vs CFI-weighted compression\r\n3. Measure prediction accuracy or reconstruction quality\r\n\r\nLet me create a concrete experiment design or implementation script.\r\n</think>\r\n\r\n### OBSERVATION\r\nThe CFI analysis revealed that 44.8% of invariants are pure noise artifacts. A concrete next step is to design and implement the CFI-weighted compression experiment to validate whether CFI filtering improves prediction quality over frequency-only baseline.\r\n\r\n### ACTION\r\nCreate `research/CFI_COMPRESSION_EXPERIMENT.md` - an experiment design for comparing CFI-weighted compression vs frequency-only baseline for next-pulse prediction.\r\n\r\n### MUTATION\r\n```\r\nold_text: (new file)\r\nnew_text: # CFI-Weighted Compression Experiment\r\n**Created:** 2026-03-24\r\n**Status:** DESIGN\r\n\r\n## Hypothesis\r\nCFI-weighted compression (filtering invariants by causal strength) will produce better next-pulse prediction than frequency-only compression.\r\n\r\n## Experiment Design\r\n\r\n### Setup\r\n- **Corpus:** Last 20 pulses (pulse_*.md files)\r\n- **Baseline:** Frequency-inverse compression (retain top N by frequency)\r\n- **Treatment:** CFI-weighted compression (retain top N by CFI * frequency)\r\n\r\n### Compression Levels\r\n- Keep top 10, 20, 50, 100 invariants\r\n- Both methods on same vocabulary\r\n\r\n### Evaluation Metric\r\n- **Reconstruction score:** How many tokens from next pulse can be predicted from compressed state?\r\n- **Semantic accuracy:** Does compressed state encode same research trajectory?\r\n\r\n## Implementation Steps\r\n1. Extract invariants from pulse corpus\r\n2. Calculate frequency scores (baseline)\r\n3. Load CFI scores from CFI_RESULTS.md\r\n4. Compute CFI-weighted scores (CFI * frequency)\r\n5. Generate compressed states at each level\r\n6. Score against held-out pulses\r\n\r\n## Expected Outcome\r\nCFI-filtered compression should match baseline at low N (signal concentrated), outperform at high N (filters noise artifacts).\r\nfile: research/CFI_COMPRESSION_EXPERIMENT.md\r\n```\n\n## For Next Instantiation\n- Proposed mutations waiting: 1\n- Completed at: 2026-03-24 10:55:19\r\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774364177738}}
